segments.text: They play it through and then they get a little closer and a little closer.
And all this time, if you don't go through it, you can't.
I don't have the words really to describe it.
But when it's over and you walk back to your dormitory in complete silence,
I mean, you don't hear anybody, you don't hear any sound anywhere.
And it, all kind of thoughts are going through your mind.
Do you remember going to Muster before the war?
No, sir.
Almost no one does.
Almost no one remembers Muster.
So I'm getting the impression that that Muster at Corregidor kind of changed that entirely.

And I've been told by two or three people that one of the reasons for that muster in the first place was to broadcast back to the families that certain young men in the tunnels on Corregidor were still alive.
that the War Department encouraged them to give away to get that message back.
All right, what about Bonfire?
Do you remember Bonfire?
Oh, yes, I remember Bonfire, but Bonfire was, I guarantee the people in Brazos County didn't like to see Bonfire come along because we just, we grabbed up any kind of wood we could anywhere, and

old sheds and i don't remember anybody ever tearing down a new barn or anything like that but how long did y'all work on it uh three four weeks and it was held on the drill field uh i'm trying to think yeah yeah on the drill field
And there was always an outhouse?
Oh, always on the top.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, always an outhouse.
And I had to think a minute where the site of it, but I remember now that's where it was on the drill field because you could come in from Melbourne Road and circle around it.
Well, you couldn't circle around either.
You could come up one side.
Yeah, you could, you could, you could.
And we had, I know we had guards out there because after it got up
old foot high or so where we had guards every night and freshmen had to guard.
But nobody tried to burn it, did they?
Not my freshman year.
Not my freshman year.
Did you attend a commencement in those days, an Aggie commencement?
No, I didn't.

okay i did not all right so you go away to the war and you said you're going to tell me about uh not coming back to to a m to finish your degree oh oh i uh i was injured in the second world war that's a pretty poor excuse but uh i when i i didn't know i was in the sir in the hospital a long time
And I didn't really know what I wanted to do.
And I finally went, got back to Laredo, make up my mind and had a couple of job offers and I tried one and took another.
And
always halfway regretted that I didn't make that effort.
And then, what I did do was, when I finally retired, which was in 1980, I decided, I believe I'll go back, Texas A&M, and
Maybe in, you know, maybe it'll take me a year and a half.
But what the hell, I don't have anything to do.
And so I called my friend Ed Cooper.
And I said, Ed, check up and see what I can do.
I said, I don't care what I get the degree in, anything I can do.
He said, I'll see what I can do.
Well, he called me and he says, Porter, he says, I want to tell you, he says, you're going to get a letter from me.
And he says, I didn't want you to think I was hiding, but not calling you, but he said, I'm just calling you to tell you that
I'll support you in whatever you want to do."
But he says, just read the letter.
Okay.
And he says, this is one of the hardest letters I ever had to write for her.
He says, you know, he says, it's been so long since you took any of those courses.
And he says, other than giving you some allowance for
being in the service and getting certain military things and so on and so forth, says none of the courses you took that are that far back would count towards a degree in today's world.
So he says, you'd just about have to start at scratch.
Well, I wanted to do, but I didn't want to do it that bad, so I dropped it right there.
Right now, don't I recognize that ring?
Yes, but let me tell you, when we went into the service, our class, everybody that was classified
as a middle of the road junior, were given permission to get an Aggie ring.
I didn't know that.
And there's no, I don't know of any
I remember.
Who made that decision, do you know?
Texas A&M made that decision.
Was it an administrative decision?
I have no idea, but I know that it was made and we were.
How much did it cost, do you remember?
It was around $60.
A lot of money.
A heck of a lot of money.
I had to pay for it in four installments.
Yes, sir.
And that's your original?
That's my ring right there.
Do you have any good ring stories?
Well.
Where you lost it and it was found or somebody in some unusual circumstances recognized it?
No.
Oh, I've had worlds of people recognize it, and more or less like you they do.
mine is worn so that they'd say, isn't that an Aggie ring?
My ring, at that time they didn't make the ring that they do now.
This ring had too much gold in it and it was too soft.
And I put all the wear on that ring and the first three years I had it nearly.
But I tell you, I wouldn't part with it.

right now what so far what have we left out about your student days that we should have included i think we've probably included more than then it's going to be worthwhile i i did as far as student days i can't think of a heck of a lot more
Can you look back now and realize some life-changing people or events from your A&M student days?
Somebody that did something that affected your life?
No, not in that respect, but...
A lot of the people that I met then did things over the years that caused me to change my life.
As I mentioned earlier, when I got out of A&M was the people I got to know.
and the connections with them.
And when I say connections, I don't mean that you're looking for something.
True, friendly, friendship connections where they just thought of each other and felt like doing things for each other and so on and so forth.
Let me tell you a story about Ed Davis.
I won't take any more of your time, but I want to.
No, no, no, I'm glad.
Ed's mother and father were great, great, great people.
And we spent nearly every weekend in Wichita Falls when we were up at Fort Sill, he and Dickie and I.
He and Dickie were roommates at A&M, by the way.
When he had gotten married, he and Janita came to Laredo, and they were going to Monterey on their honeymoon.
And they came over and I treated them to dinner and so on, and the next day they went to Monterey.
Well, I think that was a, I'm not sure if it was a Friday or a Saturday, but early Sunday morning over at the place I get a telephone call from Monterey.
He says, Garner?
Yeah.
He says, this is the head.
And I said, yeah, what can I do for you?
He says, well, I'm down here in Monterey and says,
I done run out of money.
He says, I don't know what I'm gonna do.
And I said, well, I tell you what, I said, Ed, there's a, I says, it's 10 o'clock.
I says, there's a bus leaves here at 11.
I said, now transport this Del Norte.
Can you remember that?
He said, yeah.
I says, well, I'm gonna give the driver
an envelope, and I'll have some money in there."
I says, how much do you need?
He says, oh, fifty dollars would be fine.
Of course, you've got to remember, you could rent a hotel room in Monterey for three dollars then, you know, and you could eat for a dollar and a half.
Yeah, that was a lot of money.
So I said, well he'll have the money.
He says, well I sure thank you and so on.
Well a friend of mine there overheard the conversation and he says, you got to send somebody some money in Monterey?
I said, yeah.
He says, where does he stand?
I said, he says he's at the Hotel Monterey.
He says, yeah.
He says, I got a friend there that runs a bar in the hotel.
He said, if you want me to, we can call him, and he'll give him the money, and you can just send this money to my friend.
I said, that'd sure be a lot easier.
So he calls this guy down there and tells him, go up in the hotel and give $50 to this man.
Well, the guy he's talking to doesn't speak much English, see.
So a little while, the phone rings again.
He called me the phone.
I said, hello, Garner?
He said, yeah, this is the head again.
I said, yeah, what can I do for you?
He said, listen, don't send that money.
I said, what's the matter?
He says, you know, he says, some damn fool muskin just knocked on my door and asked if I was A.W.
Davis.
And I said, yes.
He says, he handed me $50 and turned around and walked off.
He said, don't send that money.
But anyway.
Very good, very good.
I've got to tell you one thing about Earl Rudder.
I know you know a lot more about Earl Rudder than I do.
No, no.
I was on the board of the former student association one year or two years or whenever it was when Mr. Rutter was president.
And it was back during the time when we were having all this student unrest on the campuses of the United States.
And he met with us one time with our board
And you know, Jim Rutter is pretty much for calling spades spades.
And he told us, he says, you don't ever have to worry about us having these problems at Texas A&M like are happening all over everywhere else.
He says, we don't have a bunch of wild-eyed professors here.
And he says, we're not going to have.
He says, some of these security checks that we run before we hire anybody from the instructor level up, they might be illegal.
But we do them anyway, and I'll guarantee you we're not going to have that problem here at Texas A&M.
He's dead, everybody dead, but that's what he said.
And I remember a few times saying, too, if there's ever a problem, the guy that's going to be walking in front of the group to stop the problem is talking to you right now.
In other words, you're going to have to deal with me, one way or the other.
And that was very, very important.
Well, I've got two or three concluding questions, but let's go on to the Cadillac bar before we do that.
How did you get connected with it and tell me about it and describe it?
I sure will.
It belonged to my first wife's father.
His name was Mayo Besson.
Spell the last name.
B-E-S-S-A-N. B-E-S-S-A-N.
He was from Louisiana.
And he had come down there in the middle 20s, opened up a place.
Anyway, and he had reached, oh gosh, he was
in his middle 60s or so, or 70s, almost 70, 65 to 70, when I got married.
And he'd had a man that had worked for him for years over there that had had a heart attack, another Louisiana man.
And he really didn't, he was thinking about closing the place up.
But it was kind of a legend over there.
And I was working on this side, and he approached me to see if I might be interested in going over there and going to work.
I said, I think I would, but I'd like to think about it a little.
I talked to the man that I'd been working for who was an old family friend and so on and so forth, and he told me, he says, Porter, it's a great opportunity for you.
And he says, I don't want you to leave here, but I think it would be a great move.
And he says, but one thing you have to remember, you stay on one side of that bar or the other.
Don't try to work both sides of it.
And so I did.
I went over there and I went to work.
This is what year?
Last part of 47.
Oh, excuse me.
Here, Benjo.
Yellow.
So anyway, I went over there and
started working for him.
I didn't know much about the business, but I learned and met a lot of friends, made a lot of friends.
And we went through the flood over there, washed everything out, out of business for nine months, and then reopened.
And shortly after that,
He decided that he was going to get out of the business and he gave me an opportunity to buy it from him with the 10-year payout, which I was glad to have because even though he and I got along fine,
It's not easy sometimes to run a place and have the complete responsibility but not have complete authority.
And anyway, we averted any kind of problem and funny thing is fate would have it at a ten year payment
And he died 20 days after I made my last payment.
And to people who knew him and me, I always had said he wasn't going to die until he got his last payment.
Anyway, he was a fine man.
We got along well.
But it was a legend institution down there.
Describe where it was and describe it physically.
All right.
It was about three blocks into Mexico.
It was a bar room.
It had a long bar, about a 30-foot bar.
at least 30-foot bar.
And in the main dining room there in front of the bar was about, let's see, about 20 tables, and then another room behind it that had about another 20 tables, and then an old
like a dance floor, which we didn't utilize at all back before, which at one time had been a gambling room before gambling went out in Mexico in 37, I believe, 37, 38.
But anyway, we served mostly American foods.
So it was both drink, both refreshments and?
Oh yes, yes.
We, it's like most of those places, the food's what draws the people, the drinks are where you make the money.
But we always felt like we gave everybody a real run for their money.
We were very reasonable price-wise.
Who were some of the famous visitors you recall?
I had lots of those.
One time I had five governors in there.
I had the Texas governor, the New Mexico governor, and three Mexican governors in there at one time.
I had lots of celebrities that had been in and out.
had politicians of all kinds.
I mean, Jimmy Carter was there before he was president, John Connolly, all of the Kennedy clan,
distaff side.
And Lady Bird was a regular down there with her family.
And let's see.
I'll never forget the time.
Now this is an unlikely combination when the
Roy Rogers and Jack Dempsey.
Now, would you imagine those two together?
A friend of mine down there was having them down to go hunting with him.
And he brought them across the river and told me that he was going to come across with them.
And he said, I want you to do something for me.
And he told me what it was.
And I said, OK.
So they came in that morning just about the time I was opening up and he introduced me naturally to them and I said, what did you gentlemen like to drink?
And Dempsey said, I don't know, an old-fashioned or something.
He said, I'd like an old-fashioned.
And so Roy Rogers says, I'd like a Sarsaparilla.
And I said, yes, sir.
And I reached down and handed it to him.
We didn't normally have them, but he had tipped me off ahead of time that that's what he was going to ask for.
Well, I'm going to tell you that guy's eyes got about that big, because he really didn't expect anybody to have a source of perilla.
But anyway, Phil Harris used to come quite often.
He loved to hunt quail, and he'd come down there.
Now that's a guy that could handle that booze and not show it at all.
He's something else.
Come in and he'd think, I'll have a double Jack Black.
And Dizzy Dean.
Of all the famous people that came, who was the most enjoyable?
the most pleasant, positive?
Probably Leo Carrillo.
He was, of course, being Mexican, he had that ambience with all of the people that worked there and everything.
And I remember one time somebody asked him,
Of course, you have to really understand the vernacular, but somebody asked him, says, are you Spanish, Mr. Carrillo?
He said, no, I'm puro pelado.
Pelado literally means hair, but pelado is just part of the group or the barrio or something.
I'm one of the people.
That's right.
He said, no, yo soy puro pelado.
Did any of the celebrities ever become troublesome?
No, not really.
Never did.
Never did.
The nearest one was John, I've forgotten his name.
I've forgotten his last name now.
I remember he played in
in the movie The Flying Tigers with John Wayne, he was the pilot that was a hot shot or something.
I can't remember what his last name is.
John Carroll.
John Carroll.
He was a little
but it was not really bad.
All right, so you were managing that from 48 till when?
47, well, the last part of 47 till I retired in 1980.
I actually, I gave it to my employees when I left.
And Aggies knew where it was.
Oh, yes.
I mean, Gus,
Morris always said, now this is the Aggie table.
He didn't tell everybody that.
When you go down there, you go to the Aggie table.
Oh, he was a great bunch.
Well, I'm about to the end of the questions I can think of.
And here are some kind of summary questions.
What has it meant to your life that you attended Texas A&M?
What difference has it made?
All the difference in the world.
I can't think of any one happening.
that has probably had a bigger influence, other than family or children, but I can't think of anything that had a bigger influence on my life.
What did you learn at Texas A&M?
We're talking about learn now.
I know what you mean.
I know what you mean.
I think I learned to judge people.
I really, if I'd say I have any quality, I would think I'm a pretty good judge of people.
So what are the qualities of being a good Aggie?
Beg your pardon?
a good Aggie has what kind of qualities?
Well, he's true.
He's true to himself, and he's true to his friends, and he's responsible.
He's truly
He's just a true man, that's all.
Let's make believe that someone walks to your door tomorrow and hands you a check for a million dollars and attaches only one condition to that check.
